Fig. 2A and B show K′ at different concentrations of ozone and pCNB or NB, and the same results could be obtained when concentration of ozone and pCNB changed. To determine the rate constant of pCNB reacting with ozone, reaction rate constant of NB and ozone was determined first and compared with literature data. The measured rate constant of NB and ozone in this experiment was 1.2Lmol−1
s−1, which is close to the result reported by Beltran et al. [22] but very different from data reported by Honigé et al. [23] (Table 1
). Results reported by Beltran et al are several orders of magnitude higher than that of Honigé et al., which may be due to experimental design differences. A static experimental model was adopted by Honigé et al. in which definite amount of ozone, NB and radical inhibitor were added into the reactor simultaneously, and the concentration of NB was inspected during reaction. Ozone concentration was considered constant if it changed less than 20%. Since the decomposition of ozone in the process was not taken into account, the result was lower. Beltran et al. carried out the experiment with continuous flow, where ozone concentration was considered constant as well. Compared two results above, the one of Beltran et al. was thought to be more reasonable.
